%N A395471 Decimal expansion of the angle theta (in radians) such that 5*theta and theta are the half central angles of the circular arcs of a constructible squarable lune.
%C A395471 The angle in degrees is 23.439... . The second half central angle is 5*theta = 2.045... = 117.195... degrees.
%C A395471 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395471 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395467/a395467.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395471 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395471 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A395471 Equals arccos((sqrt(5+4*sqrt(5))-1)/4)/2.
%F A395471 Equals arcsin(sqrt(10-2*sqrt(5+4*sqrt(5)))/4).
%e A395471 0.409090011367742832357770863998932331682317288824086...
%t A395471 RealDigits[ArcCos[(Sqrt[5 + 4*Sqrt[5]] - 1)/4]/2, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395471 (PARI) acos((sqrt(5+4*sqrt(5))-1)/4)/2
